equires active transport into bile canaliculi","Stercobilin is excreted in faeces","Urobilinogen can be reabsorbed from the colon"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily (80%) but not exclusively produced from the breakdown of haemoglobin in senescent red blood cells. The remaining 20% comes from other haem-containing proteins such as myoglobin and cytochromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjugated bilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E requires active transport via multi-drug resistance protein 2 (MRP2) to cross into the bile canaliculi. This is an energy-dependent process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the intestine, bacterial enzymes convert conjugated bilirubin to \u003Cstrong\u003Eurobilinogen\u003C/strong\u003E. Some of this can be reabsorbed into the portal circulation. The remaining urobilinogen is converted to \u003Cstrong\u003Estercobilin\u003C/strong\u003E which gives faeces its brown colour. \u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E are essential for this conversion process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bilirubin is primarily formed from haemoglobin breakdown but also comes from other haem-containing proteins","Conjugated bilirubin requires active transport into bile canaliculi via multidrug resistance protein 2","Bacterial metabolism of bilirubin in the colon produces urobilinogen, which can be reabsorbed, and urobilin/stercobilin which are excreted"],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Fevery J. Bilirubin in clinical practice: a review. Liver Int. 2008 May;28(5):592-605. doi: 10.1111/j.1478-3231.2008.01716.x. PMID: 18433389."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52592"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15327"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52592"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T16:18:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T16:19:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8018"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a